I birded IRWS to look for what else but hummingbirds, as I had not seen a single one the whole year!  Within a few minutes of arriving, a male Ruby-throated Hummingbird gave me a brief but satisfactory look right by the Visitor Center.  I walked around the perimeter of the main part of the sanctuary, with most of my time being spent near wetlands.  A Broad-winged Hawk also made an appearance, which was an unexpected treat.  There was a noticeable amount of breeding activity going on as well.

Clear; Calm to E@5mph; Seas calm; Visibility good; Tide high falling.  We headed NE from Chatham Light inlet toward the area that had large numbers of birds 10 days ago.  Very little activity initially (almost no sea duck movement today), but at one point an Ocean Sunfish breached about 100 feet from the boat!  5+ miles out we started seeing small groups of MASH, SOSH, & LAGU.  The water was once again full of krill, which the MASH & LAGU seemed to be feeding on.  Given the calm conditions, most birds were sitting on the water.  At one point we came upon one raft of birds that had 150+ MASH!  Several widely dispersed Humpbacks 8-9 miles out were not surface feeding and had only a few birds in attendance.  Birds were widely dispersed, with no large concentrations, and were mostly a couple miles or so south of where the largest concentrations were 10 days ago.  Jaegers were widely dispersed, but most were 2-5 miles out (as usual), and with almost no terns around they were mostly going after LAGU.  In addition to birds, we saw 7-8+ Humpback Whales; 6+ Minkes, and 2 Ocean Sunfish (one breached!).
